^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, lets discuss the bidding. As East, I would personally bid 2D over 1S. If nothing else, it is good lead directing if Kia is on lead. However, assuming Sandra passes, let us discuss Kia's options. Double is possible. The other possibility is 1N. That should show 11-14. So Kia has an extra point, but it does have the advantage of describing that Kia has a balanced hands with spades. However double is acceptable. Of course Kia will not be happy if pard bids 2C, which is another argument in favor of a slightly strong 1NT. |
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Anyway, because it is a balancing double, Sandra should only bid 2D, although she has 10 points and would jump over a direct takeout double. Kia, should not pass. with 4 diamonds and 15 points, he should do something. I suggest 2S, which could be interpreted as a limit raise or better. If Sandra then happens to bid 3C to show a club stopper, Kia can bid 3N which happens to make, 5 diamonds 2 black Aces and 2 heart tricks. I am not saying they will get there, but Kia needs to at least give their side the chance to get there. |
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's talk about Ann's bidding. I think 2C was ok, and 2S was barely okay. However, once I keep passing, I think 3S is a bit much. Granted you have a powerful 2-suited hand, but you might talk the opponents into bidding 3N that way. So, tactically, I think a pass is better. You also have the problem that you could lose control of the hand as you did. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Had one of them decided to double, you would have had a real bad result, and as it is, you had a so-so result as I think the best they can do is 4D. I guess my message is, E/W was too conservative, and North was a tad aggressive. but I prefer the aggressiveness to the conservativeness, so Ann gets a b for her bidding, but E/W gets a C. |
