^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well I think everyone agrees that my hand when I was sitting South is a normal Weak-2 in diamonds, not a Howard special. LOL. I think Kia has a pass. However, if he exchanges his King of diamonds for a small diamond and 2 of hearts for K of hearts he might consider a double or 2S. In other words, with Kxxxx Kxx, xx, AJx, he is close to having a bid, although I don't like his spades. Now, normally, 3D by North should show 3. But tactically, there is some sense to bidding 3, as it makes it harder for E/W. But, North is promising 3, so she did lie. They can make 2S, but probably not 3, so the result is okay.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play, Kia did well to switch to a heart after winning the Ace of clubs. But, at trick four he should not give Declarer a ruff and sluff. I think when he wins the King of diamonds, he should just play another diamond. One more point about the defense with clubs at trick five it is very important for the defender without the Ace of clubs to give count to the defender with the Ace of clubs. So, Sandra should definitely play the two of clubs on the K of clubs. That shows holding three clubs. |
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since Kia took my counting lesson, he would then figure out Ann had 2 clubs, so he should duck the first club, as she has another one. If East had, for example, 4 clubs, then East should play her 2nd highest to show 4 clubs. Then Kia would know East started with 1 club, so he should not duck his Ace. Giving count in these situations, where there is a suit headed by the KQ in dummy and one of the defenders has the Ace is very important. Because then the person with the Ace knows when to take it, to minimize the chances of the suit being set up.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT|^B@2
nome: Is a new suit by responder to a Weak-2 always forcing for one round or by partnership agreement?|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Many people play what is known as "RONF" or "Raise Only Non-Force" which means that new suits are forcing over a Weak-2. However, there is a growing popularity to playing new suits are not forcing over a Weak-2. So, the only forcing bid is 2N. That is what I play, and I think it works better. However, it is definitely a partnership agreement, and if in doubt, assume a new suit is forcing.|
