^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, first the bidding. I would open 3H with the North hand, but most experts do not agree with me. The reason most experts don't agree is the heart suit is weak, and you have outside strength in diamonds. So, pass is fine, even if I would open 3H. Same reasoning for whether or not Kia should open 2S. His strength is outside the spade suit. Again, I like to preempt, but that is a matter of style.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I also got a question about preempting in 2nd seat. There is a good theory that you should be more cautious about preempting in second seat, as opposed to first or third seat. The reason being is that since there is already one pass, it is more likely when you are in second seat that your partner has points, because you already know that first seat has less than an opener. So, you are more likely to be preempting your partner in second seat.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since I like to preempt, and I think the rewards in general outweigh the risks, I dont worry too much about 2nd seat, but it certainly is a valid theory. On this hand, it will often be a pass out, but not if I were North or East. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Kia asked a question about the finesse. Kia should lead the Jack of spades at trick two, and finesse. There is no danger of losing control with 9 trumps--six in one hand. There is a small danger of a diamond ruff, but we have to find it after the finesse loses, and it is unlikely.|
